<h1>From Daniel Jenifer Adams</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Port-Tobacco. [Md.] March 15th 1775</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Yours of the 8th Instat, came safe to hand, wherein you mention, you have come to the resolution of taking upon your Self the payment of my Fathers debts, provided I will Suffer a Condemnation of the Attachd Effectsjoin my Sisters in Conveying the Lands to you&amp; Surrender possession of the Negroe &amp;ca.</p>
<p>To all this I and my Sisters will comply with, but Sir I think it will be very Necessary for you to give from under your hand at the time of Conveyance, that there shall no debt, or debts, hereafter come Against me, or my Sisters, that my Fathers Estate is now liable toI am in hopes Sir, After my giving up every thing I have to you, you will Set me at liberty, for I do not think I am altogether Acting the honest part, by giving up all that I am worth to you and my Other Creditors to go Intirely without, which if I was to give up to my Creditors and take the benefit of the Act, every Creditor would have an equal part, Agreeable to their Claim, which was my resolution to have Acted, but as you are such a considerable Looser, I am willing to make all Satisfaction I possibly can, and comply with the request of my Freinds, and for my Other Creditors I must trust to Providence for their lenity &amp; Favor, but I have little right to expect any Favour from them, as they do not Share a part with you, in the Estate<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-10-02-0230-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-10-02-0230-fn-0001-ptr">1</a>I have wated on Stromatt, and he gave me the Inclosd to send to you, and tells me he does not expect any thing for his Travelling expences, but thinks it reasonable he Should be paid the Cost of Suit, which Mr Clapham at Annapolis informd me would
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-10-02-pb-0303">[303]</span>
be about five pounds common Cury and what the cost of the Scirefacious will be, I am not Aquainted, but Stromatt told me it would be 3 or 4 Hundred pounds Tobacco, that paid off at 12/6 <img class="char" src="images/char-per-trans.png" alt="[per]"/> Cwt<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-10-02-0230-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-10-02-0230-fn-0002-ptr">2</a>As you Observe the Sooner matters is Settled the better I am of your Oppinion, and am ready at any time to have Matters Executed, I have wated on Some of the Creditors with your letters, and they Seem very well Satisfyd with them.</p>
<p>I have One favor to ask of your Honor, and would Strongly recommend it to you, to comply with my request, the Negroe you Attachd was brought up in the Family, has always been a favorate Negroe in the Family, and has been much Indulgd he has now a Wife and Several Children, which he seems to have a great Affection for, and has declard Several times that he will Loose his life, or had rather Submit to Death then go to Virginia to leave his Wife a[nd] Children, and do immagine from his declirations that he has made he will be Troublesome to any Master in Virginia, tho as fine a Slave as any in Maryland if you will be kind enought to favor this Poor wretch, he can get a Master who he is willing to Serve, and will give you more then he is appraisd to, which is a great price, the Fellow is about five or Six in. Thirty very hefty and well made, but Sickly, at times.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-10-02-0230-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-10-02-0230-fn-0003-ptr">3</a></p>
<p>The Horse you Attachd I Swapd away las Fall, for another Horse and gave five pounds to boot, as the Horse you Attachd was very Infurm and I was affraid he would not have got over it, but you may have this Horse Valued, as he is worth considerably more then the Other, or if you will let him Stay on the Plantation till Plowing time is Over you may have him at the Same, the Other Horse was Valued to.</p>
<p>I should Immagine the best way to Act to Save expence would be to have the Attachment Stopd as Soon as Possible and for I and my Sisters to make the Land and Effects Over to you, which I should Suppose would give you as good a Wright as if they were Condemnd by LawI am Sir Your Most Obt &amp; Most Hum. Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Danl J. Adams</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-10-02-0230-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-10-02-0230-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-10-02-0230-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>See particularly <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-10-02-0223&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-10-02-0223-fn-0002#GEWN-02-10-02-0223-fn-0002" class="document">GW to Daniel Jenifer, 8 Mar., n.2</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-10-02-0224&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-10-02-0224-fn-0003#GEWN-02-10-02-0224-fn-0003" class="document">GW to Knox &amp; Baillie, 8 Mar., n.3</a>. The deed for the 552 acres was recorded in Charles County, Md., on 5 Jan. 1776. The deed read in part: This Indenture made this fourth day of December in the year of our Lord one Thousand Seven hundred and Seventy five Between Daniel Jenifer Adams Anna Adams and
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-10-02-pb-0304">[304]</span>
Elizabeth Mason Adams of Charles County Children of Josias Adams late of the same County deceased of the one part and his Excellency General George Washington of the other part . . . in Consideration of the Sum of Five Hundred and Eighty pounds twelve Shils. Sterling Money to the said Daniel Jenifer Adams in hand paid by the said George Washington . . . and in Consideration of the Sum of twelve pounds Current money paid to the said Anna Adams and Elizabeth Mason Adams . . . Doth Grant Bargain Sell Alien release Enfeoff and Confirm unto him the said George Washington . . . all those Several Tracts and parcells of Land lying and being in Durham Parish in Charles County aforesaid that is to say. all that Tract of Land called Josiass help Containing One hundred and Nine Acres more or Less all that Tract of Land called Wades Addition Containing Thirty three Acres, and one third of an Acre all that Tract of Land Called Adamss Retirement Containing One hundred Acres more or Less All that Tract of Land Adamss Outlet Containing Fifty Acres of Land and also all that Tract of Land Called Williamss Folly containing Two Hundred and Sixty Acres more or Less, which last Tract of Land was Conveyed by James B. Muncaster to Ann Adams on the Twentyeth day of August in the One Thousand Seven hundred and Seventy three the same being all the Land which was held Occupied or Possessed by the said Josias Adams in his Lifetime (Charles County Land Records, 3:6061, Hall of Records, Annapolis).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-10-02-0230-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-10-02-0230-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>For references to dealings with John Stromatt, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-10-02-0185" class="document">Adams to GW, 4 Feb.</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-10-02-0223" class="document">GW to Daniel Jenifer, 8 Mar.</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-10-02-0223&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-10-02-0223-fn-0002#GEWN-02-10-02-0223-fn-0002" class="document">note 2</a> of that document, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-10-02-0224" class="document">GW to Knox &amp; Baillie, 8 March</a>. <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Scire facias</span> is a writ founded upon some matter of record, such as a judgment, and requiring the person against whom it is brought to show cause why the party bringing it should not have advantage of such record. The name is used to designate both the writ and the whole proceeding (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Henry Campbell Black. &lt;i&gt;Blacks Law Dictionary: Definitions of the Terms and Phrases of American and English Jurisprudence, Ancient and Modern&lt;/i&gt;. Rev. 4th ed. St. Paul, 1968. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Blacks Law Dictionary</span></span>).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-10-02-0230-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-10-02-0230-fn-0003">3</a>
 
   <p>After GW left for Boston, Lund Washington continued to attempt to persuade the slave of whom Adams is speaking to come to Mount Vernon. When the man finally arrived in January 1776, Lund Washington was very pleased with him, but he shortly wrote GW that at the slaves insistence he was going to return him to Maryland (<a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0434" class="document">Lund Washington to GW, 3</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0525" class="document">17 Dec. 1775</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0134" class="document">25 Jan.</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0198" class="document">8 Feb. 1776</a>).</p>

</div>
